#SelfAdjustment 🔥This is a simple and effective self-adjustment technique for the Sacroiliac joint (SIJ) and maybe even some vertebrae all the way up your back! Before doing this, you will want to get warmed up🏊🚴‍♀️ with some light cardio and gentle stretches🤸‍♂️. The more warm and loose your pelvis/back is, the more likely the joint will “release.” Try a couple attempts each way and if you do it right, you will hear an audible “crack” right above the buttocks🍑… you may have adjusted your own SIJ!☺️ You can try to do this on your couch, bed, coffee table, or massage table!
.
.
Don’t hurt yourself doing this! We don’t know what is going on with you obviously, this is just a tool we have given people that cannot come and see us. Ask your doctor before attempting this exercise. 👨‍⚕️This is similar to “cracking your knuckles,” and shouldn’t really hurt when you do it.
.
.
If your SIJ is in pain😭, it means that you have some muscle imbalances that are causing the pelvis to twist, forcing the joint to get locked up. Use this self-adjustment technique to help you temporarily⏲, but the joint will just lock back up🔒 again unless you address the muscle imbalances in the hips and back.
.
.
Tomorrow we will show you another stretch to open up the hip and Thursday and Friday will have some strengthening 💪exercises for you!
-💻Written by Andrew Dettelbach

✨SI JOINT DYSFUNCTION✨
If you paid attention 😜, you saw that I addressed some ways to decrease tightness and ultimately decrease stress around the sacroiliac joint with some stretches. 
Now, if you're problem is HYPERMOBILITY (increased movement) of the joint, you'll want to pay attention to today and the next couple days for progressions. 
I've addressed it before, but why not address it again! .
🔷 TRANSVERSE ABDOMINIS🔷
It's a large, deep ab muscle that I care about much more than the pretty rectus abdominis (well, kinda, I still cherish my 6 pack too 🤷‍♀️). BUT, when it comes to neutral spine alignment and learning how to engage low into the pelvic floor, I truly care about learning how to fire the TA! 
Think of the TA (transverse abdominis) like a corset 👗 When activated, it will help stabilize the spine, along with the pelvic floor muscles and multifidi (back). I love teaching how to activate the two (TA and PF) lying supine first. Place your hands on your hips bones when performing the exercises. Draw the ribs down toward the hip bones but do NOT suck in the stomach. When you suck in the stomach the ribs will flare and we lose the contraction in the TA. Practice doing this before any leg movement. 
The key is to still be able to breathe (no breath holding!), but maintain steady hips through full stability in the TA and pelvic floor muscles. 
Hopefully you notice that in the first video, my hip bones move side to side. Even though I'm stabilizing my core, I'm not maintaining the contraction low into my TA and PF, therefore my hip flexors take over and pull my knee toward my chest, rather than my core stabilizing to initiate movement. 
It is hard to feel on yourself!! I highly recommend going to see a specialist (hmm.. maybe a women's health specialist 👌) if you're having SI pain.
If you're not in pain, but still want to get better at this, which I highly recommend, pop into your local #pilates studio! 
Learning how to engage into the TA and PF is way more important for not only preventing SI dysfunction, but also lifting heavy, running faster and growing old. Pretty sure you'll fall into one of those categories 😉
